{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474075"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11777"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11777"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.11,0.1,0,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1645"},{"type":"tags","id":"1646"},{"type":"tags","id":"3557"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44873"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department five days after insertion of a ventriculo-peritoneal shunt for hydrocephalus. His mother reports that he has become unsettled and has vomited twice in the past 24 hours. He has no other significant medical history apart from the hydrocephalus. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears irritable. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His anterior fontanelle is distended and tense.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral gastroenteritis","Intracranial haemorrhage","Meningitis","Seizure disorder","Mechanical failure/blockage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of this child\u0027s presentation is \u003Cstrong\u003Emechanical failure or blockage\u003C/strong\u003E of the ventriculo-peritoneal shunt, which can occur at any time following surgery. The presentation is usually vague, causing irritability, drowsiness and vomiting, especially in young infants. Initial clinical features of hydrocephalus may reappear, as evidenced in this case by the bulging fontanelle. Older children may complain of headaches, have evidence of papilloedema and seizures. Management usually involves replacement of the defective component of the shunt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral gastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common cause of vomiting in infants and could explain the irritability. However, it would not account for the bulging fontanelle, which is a red flag sign in this clinical context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eintracranial haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication that can occur after VP shunt insertion. It may present with irritability, vomiting, and a tense fontanelle. However, the child would be expected to be more unwell and have a reduced level of consciousness. Additionally haemorrhage related to the shunt would normally by closer to the time of surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E is another potential complication of VP shunt surgery. Key features would include fever, lethargy, poor feeding and a bulging fontanelle. The absence of fever makes this diagnosis less likely. However given that an infected shunt cannot be excluded five days after surgery at the time of VP shunt revision CSF will be collected for MC\u0026amp;S.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVP shunt insertion is performed to treat hydrocephalus, not to control \u003Cstrong\u003Eseizures\u003C/strong\u003E. New onset of seizures post-operatively may indicate a complication like haemorrhage or infection. However, there is no mention of seizure activity in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ventriculo-peritoneal shunt blockage in a child can cause a vague presentation of irritability, drowsiness and vomiting which may arise anytime after surgery.","Fontanelles, if still open, can indicate whether a ventriculo-peritoneal shunt is either blocked or over-draining."],"references":["Haridas A, Tomita T. Hydrocephalus in children: Clinical features and diagnosis. 2022. Accessed  2022 May 11. Available at:  https://www.uptodate.com.acs.hcn.com.au/contents/hydrocephalus-in-children-clinical-features-and-diagnosis?search=hydrocephalus%20children\u0026topicRef=6174\u0026source=see_link","Flett P, Russo R. Neural tube defects, large heads and hydrocephalus. In South, M. \u0026 Isaacs, D. (Eds) Practical Paediatrics. Edinburgh: Churchill Livingstone/ Elsevier. 2012:613 \u2013 624."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11777"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73424"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-08T20:37:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-08T20:37:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89244"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"}